==Controversy==
Shortt has made various claims regarding his military service when interviewed or providing consultations.  In ''The Gun Digest Book of Assault Weapons'' Shortt under the alias "Seamus Shortt" is described as a "British [[Royal Marine]] ([[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|TA]])" and that "Shortt has other military training as well, but details of it are still classified".<ref name="Lewis">{{cite book|author1=Lewis, Jack |author2=Campbell, Robert K.|author3=Steele, David|title=The Gun Digest Book of Assault Weapons|edition=7th, illustrated, revised|year=2007|publisher=Gun Digest|page=129|ISBN=0-89689-498-3|chapter=The Combat Training Team|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=P75lJjon9yoC}}</ref>  In ''The SAS Fighting Techniques Handbook'', author Terry White thanked Shortt for his insights in close personal protection and [[counter-terrorism]]. White states in his acknowledgements that he believed Shortt to be a "former member of the British Parachute Regiment and Special Air Service".<ref>{{cite book |last1=White|first1=Terry|title=The SAS Fighting Techniques Handbook|accessdate=28 May 2017|year=2007|publisher=Globe Pequot|page=vii|ISBN=1-59921-081-9|chapter=Acknowledgements|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=QqWZEY-zz8AC&pg=PR7&dq=shortt+SAS}}</ref>

On 29 January 2009, the British tabloid ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' ran an article which revealed that Shortt had never belonged to either the Special Air Service (SAS) or the Parachute Regiment.  He had only been a [[Combat Medical Technician|medic]] in the [[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]] and had left within months of joining.  This matter came to light after Brian Ware, who headed the security department at the [[Cabinet Office]], was suspended for allowing Shortt on to the property without ensuring he had proper authorization or vetting his credentials. Shortt had been invited by Ware as a security advisor.<ref name="thesun.co.uk-1">{{cite news|first=Tom Newton |last=Dunn |title=Fake SAS man given Cabinet security job|url=http://thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/news/campaigns/our_boys/article2183915.ece|work=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]|date=29 January 2009|accessdate=6 February 2009|deadurl=unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201034550/http://thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/news/campaigns/our_boys/article2183915.ece|archivedate=1 February 2009}}</ref>

The following day ''The Sun'' quoted several other dubious claims listed on Shortt's CV, including his claim of being an Irish [[baron]], being made a [[Order of St. Gregory the Great|Knight Commander of St Gregory]] by Pope [[John Paul II]], as well as having a ''Gant d’Or'' ("golden gloves") in French [[Savate]] and a 9th Dan [[Black belt (martial arts)|black belt]] in traditional Japanese [[Ju Jutsu]] from the "Dai Nihon Seibukan in Kyoto, Japan".<ref name="thesun.co.uk-2">{{cite news|title=The Whip|url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/news/columnists/thewhip/article2195175.ece|work=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]|date=30 January 2009|accessdate=11 February 2009|deadurl=unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606224404/http://www.thesun.co.uk/sol/homepage/news/columnists/thewhip/article2195175.ece|archivedate=6 June 2011}}</ref>

