A '''shock site''' is a [[website]] that is intended to be offensive or disturbing to its viewers. They contain material of high [[shock value]], generally of a [[pornographic]], [[scatology|scatological]], [[graphic violence|graphically violent]], insulting, vulgar, [[profanity|profane]], or otherwise provocative nature.<ref name="shock tactics"/> Some shock sites display a single picture, [[animation]], video clip or small gallery, and are circulated via [[email]] or disguised in posts to [[discussion site]]s as a prank.<ref name="– Jason Chen">{{cite web|author=&ndash; Jason Chen |url=https://gizmodo.com/233295/fujitsu-sells-waterproof-phone-with-tub-girl |title=Fujitsu Sells Waterproof Phone With Tub Girl |publisher=Gizmodo.com |date=2007-02-01 |accessdate=2012-11-18}}</ref>  Steven Jones distinguishes these sites from those that collect galleries of shocking content, such as [[Rotten.com]], as the gallery sites must be searched for content.<ref>{{cite book|title=Porn.com: Making Sense of Online Pornography|chapter=Horrorporn/Pornhorror|last=Jones|first=Steven|editor-last=Attwood|editor-first=Feona|publisher=[[Peter Lang (publisher)|Peter Lang]]|year=2010|isbn=9781433102073|page=124|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RNprMCakFf8C&pg=PA124}}</ref>

Some shock sites have also gained their own [[subculture]]s and have become [[internet meme]]s on their own. [[Goatse.cx]] featured a page devoted to fan-submitted artwork and tributes to the site's <tt>hello.jpg</tt>,<ref name= "scotsman">{{Cite news |last= Kirkpatrick |first= Stewart |title= Lazy Guide to Net Culture: NSFW |newspaper= [[The Scotsman]] | date= 2004-06-09 | url = http://news.scotsman.com/lazyguidetonetculture/Lazy-Guide-to-Net-Culture.2535852.jp |postscript=<!--None--> |location=Edinburgh}}</ref> and a parody of the image was unwittingly shown by a [[BBC]] newscast as an alternative for [[:File:2012_Summer_Olympics_logo.svg|the then-recently unveiled logo]] for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]].<ref name="shock tactics">Herrmann, Steve. "[http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/theeditors/2007/06/shock_tactics.html Shock tactics]." ''[[BBC]]''. June 5, 2007. Retrieved on February 23, 2009.</ref> A 2007 shock video known as ''[[2 Girls 1 Cup]]'' also quickly became an Internet phenomenon, with videos of reactions, homages, and parodies widely posted on video sharing sites such as [[YouTube]].<ref name="vh1">{{cite web|author=11/20/07 |url=http://www.vh1.com/video/play.jhtml?id=1574705&vid=190222 |title="Best Week Ever: Full Act 4" &#124; Show Clip |publisher=VH1.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-18}}</ref>

